1231
02:13:08,610 --> 02:13:22,461
And I'd love to have that as a document for us to be able to refer to and kind of have a cleanup at the end of this zoning process and not wait until an additional process, because while some communities zone regularly, Medford does not have a history of doing so.

1232
02:13:25,490 --> 02:13:28,433
My second comment- Really quickly on that one, Ari.

1233
02:13:28,974 --> 02:13:47,132
We have kind of a third track going, which is called, we're calling it PDS building cleanup, which is we've had at least one meeting in the planning and permitting committee where we have a list of a bunch of stuff from PDS, a bunch of stuff from the building department, and some of the things that you just mentioned.

1234
02:13:47,732 --> 02:13:55,014
where we want to do essentially a cleanup of the whole ordinance, and we're keeping a list.

1235
02:13:55,434 --> 02:13:57,454
I'm seeing Danielle nod that we have a long list.

1236
02:13:57,674 --> 02:14:00,935
So just so you know, we are doing that, and we want to do that.

1237
02:14:00,955 --> 02:14:09,657
It's kind of its own process, and the intent is to do that, but outside of the INIS process that we're doing for Medford Square and Boston F. Sorry to interrupt you.

1238
02:14:12,352 --> 02:14:12,632
Lovely.

1239
02:14:12,692 --> 02:14:14,013
I was hoping that would be the answer.

1240
02:14:14,053 --> 02:14:15,955
I figured it would be.

1241
02:14:16,715 --> 02:14:20,718
And I'm glad that we all can know that now.

1242
02:14:22,219 --> 02:14:27,703
My second comment is about this idea of changing the neighborhood.

1243
02:14:27,723 --> 02:14:31,466
I respectfully disagree with chair car.

1244
02:14:31,586 --> 02:14:32,767
I don't think there is

1245
02:14:34,005 --> 02:14:36,626
That zoning is about a clear intent in this case.

1246
02:14:36,666 --> 02:14:38,948
This isn't something like the transom overlay.

1247
02:14:39,348 --> 02:14:42,470
We are creating the permissions and allowances.

1248
02:14:43,290 --> 02:14:45,631
And this is a vibrant area that is growing.

1249
02:14:45,751 --> 02:14:46,972
Tufts is always growing.

1250
02:14:47,012 --> 02:14:50,654
There are large buildings and very vibrant businesses there.

1251
02:14:51,074 --> 02:14:57,918
And we are saying that if someone wants to upscale, they're already, frankly, not single family houses.

1252
02:14:58,532 --> 02:15:02,073
that that is a reasonable thing that doesn't need special permissions.

1253
02:15:02,973 --> 02:15:14,196
And I think that that is a permission that, even if you think is not appropriate for everywhere in Medford, is, I think, very, very appropriate to this specific corridor.

1254
02:15:16,097 --> 02:15:25,700
And that we should be kind of remembering that this is not about a specific intent, unlike Transom, where there was a specific vision.

1255
02:15:27,488 --> 02:15:30,371
And that the vision here is much larger.

1256
02:15:30,391 --> 02:15:35,295
About co-housing, kind of onto my third comment.

1257
02:15:35,995 --> 02:15:38,718
I'm a big fan of co-housing, co-living.

1258
02:15:38,738 --> 02:15:42,941
I think lodging houses, there are understandable concerns.

1259
02:15:42,961 --> 02:15:44,483
I think they're a very important

1260
02:15:45,684 --> 02:16:00,711
Part of the low cost housing picture that has really disappeared over the last 50 to 100 years and that we should not be banning and I'm excited to see us permitting it with kind of the necessary.

1261
02:16:02,572 --> 02:16:05,033
Safety constraints with.

1262
02:16:06,535 --> 02:16:09,019
Parking that's something that will obviously discuss.

1263
02:16:09,099 --> 02:16:09,981
We always do.

1264
02:16:10,001 --> 02:16:14,908
I think there are plenty of tools in our toolbox that.

1265
02:16:16,110 --> 02:16:20,013
for specific projects where we can limit the impact of that.

1266
02:16:20,073 --> 02:16:22,795
This is also a corridor that is very close to the Green Line.

1267
02:16:23,416 --> 02:16:37,466
And from experience of living in co-ops in my 20s, there's a lot of people who are very excited about not having cars who live in that sort of community, especially more on the planned co-living or planned co-housing.

1268
02:16:37,766 --> 02:16:39,087
Sorry.

1269
02:16:39,387 --> 02:16:43,370
But the planned communities, a lot of people who are intentionally car-free.

1270
02:16:47,031 --> 02:16:57,414
It sounds like we've talked about setbacks, but I'd like to explicitly talk about wanting to make sure there's permission and encouragement for outdoor seating for cafes and other businesses.

1271
02:16:57,494 --> 02:17:07,458
I think that is something that brings a lot of value and personality to that neighborhood, as well as all neighborhoods, and that can be an often unintended consequence.

1272
02:17:08,398 --> 02:17:11,839
And then the last one is just a small comment about animal shelters.

1273
02:17:11,919 --> 02:17:13,780
I'm not really sure where we are on that.

1274
02:17:14,620 --> 02:17:21,665
There is a cat rescue outside of Medford Square that I think is not a model for the rest of the city.

1275
02:17:22,485 --> 02:17:29,469
So if we talk about it, I would want to make sure how are we talking about doing this responsibly and ethically.

1276
02:17:29,489 --> 02:17:42,417
And that's obviously zoning is not enforcement of sanitation laws, but that I think it is something that can be important and can be done, not ideally.

1277
02:17:46,011 --> 02:17:53,678
And kind of broad vision, I'm really excited to see this as a vibrant place with lots of housing and lots of businesses.

1278
02:17:54,459 --> 02:18:03,366
There's a lot of people there and kind of living there, going out for coffee, going on the green line, taking the bus, going to school, going to local jobs.

1279
02:18:03,386 --> 02:18:09,512
And this is a vibrant area that will hopefully continue to grow over the next 20, 30, 50, 100 years.

1280
02:18:16,763 --> 02:18:18,965
All right, and I will recognize Director Hunt.

1281
02:18:20,146 --> 02:18:20,607
Good evening.

1282
02:18:20,727 --> 02:18:30,256
Just because both of the last two members mentioned the whole setbacks in the residential, I do want to flag for people that this, we did carry this through into this version.

1283
02:18:30,736 --> 02:18:37,403
So, if you were to look in the 983 dimensional requirements after the table, the next page, which is currently 18, has both

1284
02:18:42,467 --> 02:18:45,129
setbacks, but it has side and rear setbacks.

1285
02:18:45,589 --> 02:18:56,455
If it's adjacent to a residential district with a residential use of four units or fewer, the applicant shall provide a landscape buffer of at least 10 feet from the line.

1286
02:18:56,855 --> 02:19:01,958
And so that would be right now, this is all surrounded by general residential, so all of that would

1287
02:19:02,438 --> 02:19:02,999
require it.

1288
02:19:03,440 --> 02:19:08,625
And then we included the height transition, which is the whole 45 degree angles.

1289
02:19:08,745 --> 02:19:18,275
So if you are allowed to do something tall, but you're adjacent to residential, then you have to do the math on the angles and stuff.

1290
02:19:18,355 --> 02:19:23,721
And somebody had commented that the daylight standard was not here or different, but it is

1291
02:19:24,602 --> 02:19:32,705
It was carried, it was copied and pasted over, so it is the same as the version that was passed in the end of the Medford Square.

1292
02:19:35,326 --> 02:19:36,227
Right, right.

1293
02:19:36,307 --> 02:19:42,349
And again, the maximum setback of 20 feet is allowed to create an act of public pauses in there.

1294
02:19:42,889 --> 02:19:52,933
So I just wanted to address there won't be a change to address those comments because those are already in there, unless somebody thinks that what is in there should change.

1295
02:19:55,525 --> 02:20:07,817
Yeah, and we also included the step backs, which is the six story and above has to be stepped back so that it doesn't look like a straight up tower that it, you don't see it as clearly.

1296
02:20:07,837 --> 02:20:11,981
All right.

1297
02:20:12,101 --> 02:20:12,781
Thank you, Ari.

1298
02:20:12,841 --> 02:20:15,464
I'll go to Chair Carr and then John Anderson.

1299
02:20:16,758 --> 02:20:17,298
Appreciate that.

1300
02:20:17,939 --> 02:20:35,786
I think what would be helpful for the city board going forward is something that Ennis did very successfully in Meffitt Square, which was a series of sections on some of these transitions so we could see the setbacks and we could see how it goes from five stories to four stories to three.

1301
02:20:35,806 --> 02:20:44,230
There are brilliant diagrams that I think help visualize for the whole city board these transitions so that we could understand them better and clearly

1302
02:20:44,930 --> 02:20:52,094
some of the ones here where we're going from single family or general residential to upwards of 80 feet, like those are the ones that are going to be the most critical.

1303
02:20:52,114 --> 02:21:11,646
So I leave it to Ines and the group to try to just pick and choose the ones that I think would help tell the story and prove and demonstrate visually, graphically, how that transition can happen so that we do not negatively impact a person who's been living there for a decade or 20 years or a house that's been there for 100 years.

1304
02:21:11,846 --> 02:21:12,146
Thank you.

1305
02:21:13,680 --> 02:21:16,021
Thank you, and I'll go to John Anderson.

1306
02:21:19,101 --> 02:21:19,541
Thank you.

1307
02:21:21,202 --> 02:21:23,482
My comments are sort of in random order.

1308
02:21:23,522 --> 02:21:26,743
I've just been sort of scribbling things down as topics came up.

1309
02:21:28,403 --> 02:21:35,485
First, I hate to do this, but I have to respectfully disagree with Director Hunt about two and a half stories versus three stories.

1310
02:21:36,345 --> 02:21:43,587
I think they do make a big visual difference, but, you know, I guess that's a matter of personal opinion.

1311
02:21:47,005 --> 02:21:50,708
We have Tufts Institutional, of course, cut out from the corridor.

1312
02:21:52,310 --> 02:21:59,717
I guess my question is, is Tufts Institutional because that is land owned by Tufts?

1313
02:22:01,498 --> 02:22:04,721
And where does Walnut Hill fall into this?

1314
02:22:05,542 --> 02:22:09,126
Does Walnut Hill have properties that are in the corridor?

1315
02:22:10,255 --> 02:22:14,476
Is Walnut Hill considered part of Tufts for this discussion or not?

1316
02:22:15,556 --> 02:22:23,838
Generally, the institutional zone is around the campus proper, mostly properties owned by trustees of Tufts College.

1317
02:22:24,939 --> 02:22:27,399
There are a couple of things on either side of the line.

1318
02:22:27,419 --> 02:22:30,880
There's a couple of trustees of Tufts College, maybe one that falls into the

1319
02:22:31,540 --> 02:22:33,321
boundaries of the Boston Avenue corridor.

1320
02:22:33,781 --> 02:22:36,162
There's a couple Walnut Hill properties.

1321
02:22:36,222 --> 02:22:42,845
I think, actually, that's in some of the documents that there's a map that Innes made showing that ownership.

1322
02:22:43,585 --> 02:22:53,469
But generally, the Tufts Institutional is the campus and the nonprofit, Dover Exempt, relatively geographically contiguous Tufts.

1323
02:22:55,250 --> 02:22:56,630
Yeah.

1324
02:22:56,770 --> 02:23:00,532
Are there buildings in the corridor

1325
02:23:01,248 --> 02:23:03,229
that are Dover Amendment protected?

1326
02:23:03,249 --> 02:23:07,412
I'll go to Director Hunt on that.

1327
02:23:08,193 --> 02:23:19,240
So I think the way to address it is that it's Dover protected if Tufts owns the property and says we are using this for an educational use.

1328
02:23:19,741 --> 02:23:22,803
So right now there is a building

1329
02:23:23,463 --> 02:23:34,528
in the BA1 area that is owned by Tufts, but they have not stated that they are currently used, it's not in use, it's a vacant building, right?

1330
02:23:34,788 --> 02:23:37,549
So it's not being used for the educational purposes.

1331
02:23:38,149 --> 02:23:43,971
They could come forward with a proposal that says, here's our educational use, this is Dover protected.

1332
02:23:44,532 --> 02:23:45,252
They might not.

1333
02:23:46,212 --> 02:23:56,641
So to sort of enhance what President Behrs was saying is that the idea is part of the area is a campus, feels like a campus and should be treated like a campus, right?

1334
02:23:57,101 --> 02:24:05,247
If you go up on the green on the hill, do we care how far apart Tufts builds various buildings or when they attach them to each other or whatever?

1335
02:24:05,648 --> 02:24:08,630
That's their campus and it should feel like a campus.

1336
02:24:09,231 --> 02:24:12,914
When Tufts owns buildings on our city streets,

1337
02:24:13,614 --> 02:24:16,478
Then they should actually feel like they blend into the neighborhood.

1338
02:24:16,959 --> 02:24:22,106
And so there are some I'm looking to see if we have street names on here because I don't know them off the top of my head.

1339
02:24:22,567 --> 02:24:24,249
But this was sort of the other item.

1340
02:24:24,630 --> 02:24:24,830
Right.

1341
02:24:24,870 --> 02:24:30,178
So they own properties on Tesla Edison Cape and Street.

1342
02:24:30,758 --> 02:24:34,282
Emory that area but that's part of the neighborhood.

1343
02:24:34,743 --> 02:24:36,845
So right now those are not on the table at all.

1344
02:24:37,206 --> 02:24:44,154
That would be under the residential zoning but it's our general professional opinion that those should not be zoned like a campus.

1345
02:24:44,534 --> 02:24:46,617
Those should be zoned like a neighborhood.

1346
02:24:46,977 --> 02:24:50,801
And so that's where the distinction is between Tufts institutional zoning.

1347
02:24:51,662 --> 02:25:02,389
And along Boston Ave, whether or not they own it, we feel like it should be zoned like a small downtown commercial district and not like a campus.

1348
02:25:02,909 --> 02:25:06,651
That's kind of the distinction that we're getting at with the two different zones.

1349
02:25:07,291 --> 02:25:17,558
And part of what President Behrs had said earlier about not really going to have a fully baked Tufts zoning this quickly is because as we go through it,

1350
02:25:18,498 --> 02:25:24,201
We don't think we should just take the Medford Square zoning and adapt it to Tufts campus.

1351
02:25:24,261 --> 02:25:25,561
That doesn't make sense.

1352
02:25:26,082 --> 02:25:32,504
We should just look at it and say what kind of zoning is appropriate on a campus like this.

1353
02:25:33,025 --> 02:25:39,908
And we have said to Tufts, to the consultants, to other people, can somebody give us a copy of

1354
02:25:40,488 --> 02:25:45,995
institutional zoning you like from somewhere else, and nobody has come up with an example.

1355
02:25:46,155 --> 02:25:56,867
They've all said, no, we don't like that, we don't like that, we don't like that, and we don't like that, but nobody's given us a template to work with, which is meaning it takes more time if we all have to come up with this from scratch.

1356
02:25:57,908 --> 02:26:04,134
At this time, it's on Innis Agency to come up with this from scratch, not my office.

1357
02:26:04,154 --> 02:26:05,695
So even Harvard doesn't have such a thing?

1358
02:26:05,855 --> 02:26:06,696
We don't like it.

1359
02:26:06,936 --> 02:26:07,937
No, that's the thing.

1360
02:26:07,977 --> 02:26:12,421
Tufts doesn't like the zoning that Cambridge has for Harvard or their zoning for MIT.

1361
02:26:12,782 --> 02:26:15,624
There's a lot of zoning for different universities in Boston.

1362
02:26:15,664 --> 02:26:17,246
They said, don't look at those.

1363
02:26:17,266 --> 02:26:18,967
There's zoning for Brandeis.

1364
02:26:18,987 --> 02:26:20,469
They're like, no, we don't like that one.

1365
02:26:21,109 --> 02:26:24,192
Nobody's come up with one and said, actually, this works well.

1366
02:26:25,202 --> 02:26:27,283
But maybe Waltham likes the zoning.

1367
02:26:27,403 --> 02:26:28,523
We might be the first.

1368
02:26:28,743 --> 02:26:32,965
Maybe we'll come up with the first institutional zoning that people like.

1369
02:26:33,145 --> 02:26:33,645
I don't know.

1370
02:26:34,706 --> 02:26:36,787
I get a little punchy late at night.

1371
02:26:39,648 --> 02:26:47,191
About co-housing, I noticed for parking, it said 1.5 per dwelling unit.

1372
02:26:47,991 --> 02:26:51,853
How do you determine the number of dwelling units in a co-housing situation?

1373
02:26:55,602 --> 02:26:56,522
Great question.

1374
02:26:57,363 --> 02:26:58,843
Great question.

1375
02:27:00,624 --> 02:27:04,726
Usually so there's co-living and co-housing co-living.

1376
02:27:04,846 --> 02:27:08,247
If you remember was like one house with a lot of people in it.

1377
02:27:08,767 --> 02:27:12,429
Co-housing is typically multiple small units.

1378
02:27:12,969 --> 02:27:20,197
that have also some larger shared spaces that they use together frequently for cooking meals and stuff like that.

1379
02:27:20,898 --> 02:27:23,000
So technically you would have it.

1380
02:27:23,381 --> 02:27:28,807
You would be able to count up the multiple small units that exist is 1.5 the right number.

1381
02:27:30,008 --> 02:27:37,053
I don't know, but I agreed to not debate residential parking limits other than what we've been doing so far.

1382
02:27:37,513 --> 02:27:46,780
Right now they could apply for the lower, you know, do the incentives, join a TMA, have bike parking, that kind of stuff, and they could have the lower parking too.

1383
02:27:47,670 --> 02:27:51,571
So co-housing versus what was the alternative?

1384
02:27:52,032 --> 02:27:55,073
Co-living, which is what we were talking about.

1385
02:27:55,093 --> 02:28:06,437
At the beginning of the meeting, we were discussing co-living, which is the idea that are you regulating who all is in the unit together with each other, right?

1386
02:28:06,597 --> 02:28:11,059
One big unit, that was the example of each bedroom having its own bathroom.

1387
02:28:11,579 --> 02:28:20,363
and a lock on the door is very different from everybody has their own unit that they lease separately but they agree to a shared.

1388
02:28:20,663 --> 02:28:30,788
And the huge difference is like other that like they agree to their shared community values and living together as part of living there.

1389
02:28:31,409 --> 02:28:31,749
Right.

1390
02:28:31,889 --> 02:28:40,113
But OK but co-living I still don't understand how you would define dwelling units in co-living.

1391
02:28:40,969 --> 02:28:42,190
Just number of bedrooms?

1392
02:28:43,791 --> 02:28:46,013
Is that in the list at this time?

1393
02:28:46,373 --> 02:28:48,235
I think it's not in the list at this time, right?

1394
02:28:48,255 --> 02:28:48,595
It's not.

1395
02:28:48,695 --> 02:28:50,717
It's not in the use table.

1396
02:28:50,897 --> 02:28:51,938
So co-living's out.

1397
02:28:53,360 --> 02:28:55,141
We didn't feel that it was necessary.

1398
02:28:55,161 --> 02:28:59,103
I think, I don't know if you want to, Councilor Callahan, take it away.

1399
02:28:59,524 --> 02:29:00,544
If I may, thank you.

1400
02:29:01,685 --> 02:29:11,712
I will admit that I'm slightly sad that the word, the definition of co-living has ever been brought up again because it literally, we removed it because it doesn't mean anything.

1401
02:29:12,352 --> 02:29:19,177
It was, we had a reason why we thought we, it might be useful in some way, but it really is like a rental unit.

1402
02:29:20,102 --> 02:29:20,382
That's all.

1403
02:29:20,502 --> 02:29:26,386
It's just the way that all sorts of people live in a rental unit that don't happen to be a family.

1404
02:29:27,086 --> 02:29:29,187
But we've already removed the whole definition of family.

1405
02:29:29,227 --> 02:29:31,308
So literally, it just means a rental unit.

1406
02:29:31,408 --> 02:29:32,269
It doesn't mean anything.

1407
02:29:32,649 --> 02:29:35,771
So we should just not, don't worry about co-living.

1408
02:29:35,811 --> 02:29:37,692
Co-housing is actually quite different.

1409
02:29:38,192 --> 02:29:39,133
There's one in Malden.

1410
02:29:39,653 --> 02:29:40,854
There's one in JP.

1411
02:29:42,055 --> 02:29:47,058
There are two in Cambridge, and that is architecturally a very, very different thing.

1412
02:29:47,098 --> 02:29:51,562
So you're not ever going to confuse a two-family with co-housing.

1413
02:29:51,662 --> 02:29:55,104
Co-housing has like 20 or 30 units.

1414
02:29:55,925 --> 02:30:02,790
Every unit is a completely separate, just like an apartment, except they're often a little bit small, because they will have

1415
02:30:03,770 --> 02:30:06,271
they'll have like shared rooms.

1416
02:30:06,491 --> 02:30:16,316
So there will be a different building often that might have a cafeteria, like a kitchen and a seating area where people can, where maybe up to 20 people could eat together.

1417
02:30:16,896 --> 02:30:22,839
They might have, and then different places, depending on who lives there, have different shared rooms.

1418
02:30:22,899 --> 02:30:30,722
So they might have a guest room that anyone can sort of sign out and have an out-of-town guest stay in.

1419
02:30:31,102 --> 02:30:32,803
And that would be in the, like a,

1420
02:30:33,283 --> 02:30:34,784
jointly owned building.

1421
02:30:34,804 --> 02:30:46,128
These are architecturally very different and usually people spend like 15 years putting together a community and then building in different architectural buildings.

1422
02:30:46,168 --> 02:30:52,731
So co-housing is actually a very, very different thing architecturally that we do not have any of in Medford.

1423
02:30:54,552 --> 02:30:56,013
I'm happy to talk more about it.

1424
02:30:56,133 --> 02:30:59,955
Anyone who is interested, I would love to talk to you more after the meeting.

1425
02:30:59,995 --> 02:31:06,039
But co-housing is a completely different, and co-living is literally, it's just, let's not even mention it because it's just a rental unit.

1426
02:31:06,179 --> 02:31:08,461
I'm surprised there's no co-housing in Medford.

1427
02:31:08,521 --> 02:31:13,584
I seem to recall reading about one that was being proposed 10 or 15 years ago.

1428
02:31:13,644 --> 02:31:14,665
I guess it never happened.

1429
02:31:15,145 --> 02:31:16,966
There is no co-housing in Medford currently.

1430
02:31:18,169 --> 02:31:21,010
Okay, not to beat this to death, but here goes.

1431
02:31:21,510 --> 02:31:26,450
So co-living, so six or eight people decide to share a large house.

1432
02:31:27,891 --> 02:31:29,351
That would be one dwelling unit.

1433
02:31:31,831 --> 02:31:40,273
Yeah, and we can't regulate or control that, so it's not definable and it's not really a zoning question.

1434
02:31:40,553 --> 02:31:45,174
So they get one and a half parking spaces at one car, okay.

1435
02:31:46,394 --> 02:31:46,894
Well, I mean...

1436
02:31:50,133 --> 02:31:51,194
I'm just trying to understand.

1437
02:31:51,234 --> 02:31:52,276
I'm not... No, no, no.

1438
02:31:52,356 --> 02:31:53,877
I'm just trying to illustrate the point, right?

1439
02:31:53,938 --> 02:31:54,138
Sure.

1440
02:31:56,360 --> 02:32:09,035
There might be a single family house right now that has six bedrooms, but it already exists, so the parking is completely... If it already exists, it could be used for that, and the parking regulation doesn't even come into effect, right?

1441
02:32:09,055 --> 02:32:10,617
Well, or they're just parking on the street.

1442
02:32:11,333 --> 02:32:11,473
Right.

1443
02:32:11,493 --> 02:32:24,142
I'm just saying like so many of the units in the city have almost no relationship to the things in the parking code because they predate the zoning or are otherwise like they weren't they're not under construction.

1444
02:32:24,682 --> 02:32:24,862
Right.

1445
02:32:27,744 --> 02:32:29,525
Side setbacks of zero.

1446
02:32:30,386 --> 02:32:35,489
That means buildings are built right up against each other with a shared exterior wall.

1447
02:32:38,011 --> 02:32:38,131
OK.

1448
02:32:39,793 --> 02:32:41,854
The fire department has no problem with that.

1449
02:32:46,678 --> 02:32:48,859
There's there's building code to allow it.

1450
02:32:48,999 --> 02:32:51,941
If you walk down Medford Square you'll see a lot of buildings like that.

1451
02:32:52,042 --> 02:32:55,204
Basically you just have to have fire rated walls in between them.

1452
02:32:56,144 --> 02:33:00,688
You either have to have fire rated walls or I think the number is 10 feet separation.

1453
02:33:02,129 --> 02:33:05,231
So it's builders choose to do fire separate firewalls.

1454
02:33:05,531 --> 02:33:05,631
OK.

1455
02:33:12,668 --> 02:33:23,898
I looked at the recording of the April 30th public meeting and I'm trying to figure out what I learned from it.

1456
02:33:23,938 --> 02:33:32,826
The residents were asked to provide input as to how the zoning should be done in the corridor.

1457
02:33:33,407 --> 02:33:35,288
They didn't have this level of detail.

1458
02:33:35,669 --> 02:33:36,609
They had the maps.

1459
02:33:37,110 --> 02:33:37,951
They had the maps.

1460
02:33:40,098 --> 02:33:45,742
I don't think they had any concept of what was being proposed.

1461
02:33:46,062 --> 02:33:54,708
The biggest thing I heard was, no more tall buildings.

1462
02:33:56,329 --> 02:34:00,032
I guess my question is, who are the stakeholders?

1463
02:34:01,921 --> 02:34:08,644
that we're working, that who are the stakeholders who we're serving with our zoning proposal.

1464
02:34:09,024 --> 02:34:14,126
And I was really glad that you included the, where is it?

1465
02:34:16,347 --> 02:34:18,628
The purpose, the purpose.

1466
02:34:19,928 --> 02:34:25,951
And I didn't see that really being communicated to the residents.

1467
02:34:26,651 --> 02:34:28,151
And I think that's an opportunity.

1468
02:34:37,969 --> 02:34:47,377
Page 16 talks a lot about reinforcing non-vehicular travel between adjacent neighborhoods.

1469
02:34:48,177 --> 02:35:01,228
It sounds like the village concept, a self-contained village where people work and live and shop in the same contiguous area, which would include adjacent residential areas, I guess.

1470
02:35:03,720 --> 02:35:11,385
I'm having a hard time visualizing that on Boston Ave, which is also a main thoroughfare of sorts during rush hour.

1471
02:35:16,869 --> 02:35:20,191
Am I the only one who thinks that this is a problem?

1472
02:35:23,113 --> 02:35:23,693
I guess so.

1473
02:35:25,114 --> 02:35:26,756
We'll see what the residents have to say.

1474
02:35:27,536 --> 02:35:29,057
I just would encourage...

1475
02:35:31,705 --> 02:35:36,128
enough communication so the residents know what's being, what's really being proposed.

1476
02:35:39,411 --> 02:35:39,771
Thank you.

1477
02:35:39,871 --> 02:35:40,231
That's it.

1478
02:35:42,693 --> 02:35:43,534
Thank you, John.

1479
02:35:44,814 --> 02:35:48,937
Do we have any more questions from members of the Community Development Board?

1480
02:35:54,461 --> 02:35:54,741
All right.

1481
02:35:54,782 --> 02:35:55,302
Excuse me.

1482
02:35:55,322 --> 02:35:57,283
I have one other, I have a request.

1483
02:35:59,385 --> 02:36:00,345
I love the new maps.

1484
02:36:01,393 --> 02:36:06,679
Would it be possible to get ones with a building number, street numbers on it?

1485
02:36:07,360 --> 02:36:11,966
That would simplify walking around and understanding what's really going on.

1486
02:36:12,066 --> 02:36:13,668
It would simplify it tremendously.

1487
02:36:15,898 --> 02:36:17,439
At least the ones on the board, yeah.

1488
02:36:18,580 --> 02:36:30,408
We had a similar problem in Medford Square, where the maps, the color coding was very confusing, and I had to ask three times for that to be fixed before it happened.

1489
02:36:30,949 --> 02:36:43,157
So if early on we could get maps that help us with numbers, so you can walk around, you know, walking court is not so bad, but you get into some of the other areas and you get tired of sort of counting little boxes.

1490
02:36:45,754 --> 02:36:48,437
I don't know if Director Hunt or Paula, you have some?

1491
02:36:48,697 --> 02:36:53,203
We were just discussing what you could or could not see.

1492
02:36:53,223 --> 02:36:57,508
I mean, we could try and print, like GIS could display those numbers.

1493
02:36:57,768 --> 02:37:01,552
We could do a version for the board members to use for their purposes.

1494
02:37:03,154 --> 02:37:08,999
If you printed numbers big enough to read them you wouldn't be able to see the outlines of the buildings that you currently see.

1495
02:37:09,460 --> 02:37:09,680
Right.

1496
02:37:09,720 --> 02:37:12,122
So it's sort of like what do you it might be.

1497
02:37:12,582 --> 02:37:15,965
You might also need a magnifying glass to see the building numbers so.

1498
02:37:20,730 --> 02:37:23,492
And the names of the streets are there.

1499
02:37:23,792 --> 02:37:26,675
So you would know you've hit a new block by the name of the street.

1500
02:37:27,478 --> 02:37:30,480
Maybe we can take that offline because it's just a logistical thing.

1501
02:37:30,500 --> 02:37:32,221
Let's just discuss that after the meeting.

1502
02:37:32,281 --> 02:37:35,283
I just wanted to mention the interactive viewer.

1503
02:37:35,523 --> 02:37:42,807
And there you can just put the name of the street, the number, and you can access directly to see exactly which building you want.

1504
02:37:44,228 --> 02:37:47,750
We will have to upload for Boston Avenue.

1505
02:37:48,070 --> 02:37:48,370
OK.

1506
02:37:49,571 --> 02:37:49,871
All right.

1507
02:37:49,951 --> 02:37:51,492
Yeah, we're going to take this discussion offline.

1508
02:37:51,712 --> 02:37:52,152
Thank you.

1509
02:37:55,312 --> 02:38:05,243
Seeing no further discussion by members of the Community Development Board or the council, anything else you want to say to close out before we move to some public comment?

1510
02:38:07,905 --> 02:38:08,426
Chair Carr?

1511
02:38:08,926 --> 02:38:10,728
Let's proceed to the public comments.

1512
02:38:11,609 --> 02:38:11,910
All right.

1513
02:38:12,550 --> 02:38:12,851
Okay.

1514
02:38:12,871 --> 02:38:16,775
So we're going to move to some public comment.

1515
02:38:19,059 --> 02:38:25,582
If you would like to speak on Zoom, and again, I just want to clarify, I know I said this at the beginning of the meeting, but that was now two and a half hours ago.

1516
02:38:25,702 --> 02:38:29,444
So this is not the public hearing for this proposal.

1517
02:38:29,484 --> 02:38:31,305
This is an initial discussion.

1518
02:38:31,345 --> 02:38:33,706
The city council is the only body taking a vote tonight.

1519
02:38:34,066 --> 02:38:39,609
We would be voting to refer the Boston Avenue Neighborhood Corridor District to the Community Development Board.

1520
02:38:41,309 --> 02:38:42,750
If you'd like to speak at this point,

1521
02:38:43,581 --> 02:39:01,354
You're welcome to make a comment, but if you want your comments officially recorded for the record, you should come to the June 3rd public hearing, which is the next time that we'll be holding the public hearing on this matter as a joint body of the City Council and the Community Development Board.

1522
02:39:02,154 --> 02:39:08,299
We do have, you know, at least one person who has

1523
02:39:09,593 --> 02:39:11,454
who wants to speak tonight here in the room.

1524
02:39:11,755 --> 02:39:15,297
They represent a property owner in the area.

1525
02:39:15,437 --> 02:39:17,839
So that is one person.

1526
02:39:17,959 --> 02:39:24,464
If there's other folks who would like to speak, please raise your hand on Zoom and we'll alternate between in-person and on Zoom.

1527
02:39:24,484 --> 02:39:26,746
So we'll start in-person in the chamber.

1528
02:39:29,207 --> 02:39:30,869
You can come up here if that's okay.

1529
02:39:30,889 --> 02:39:33,551
And we'll just move this microphone over here.

1530
02:39:33,571 --> 02:39:34,391
Yeah.

1531
02:39:35,852 --> 02:39:36,333
And if you could,

1532
02:39:37,552 --> 02:39:38,533
Yeah, we'll get you.

1533
02:39:44,537 --> 02:39:44,917
All right.

1534
02:39:47,279 --> 02:39:50,641
So your microphone should be on and you should be able to share.

1535
02:39:52,082 --> 02:39:53,983
There we go.

1536
02:39:59,847 --> 02:40:01,849
Looks like we have about four people.

1537
02:40:01,869 --> 02:40:04,851
I'm going to keep it to about five minutes each.

1538
02:40:05,605 --> 02:40:05,945
Thank you.

1539
02:40:06,106 --> 02:40:07,467
I appreciate the time.

1540
02:40:07,808 --> 02:40:10,411
My name is David Roach.

1541
02:40:10,531 --> 02:40:14,456
I'm an independent development advisory consultant.

1542
02:40:15,227 --> 02:40:19,588
here working with one of the property owners in the proposed BA3 zone.

1543
02:40:20,168 --> 02:40:25,950
I just want to start by saying that thank you to the members of the council, the board, and planning staff.

1544
02:40:25,970 --> 02:40:29,971
You guys have done a fantastic job with this process so far.

1545
02:40:29,991 --> 02:40:33,552
It took a few minutes before I came here tonight to buzz through the agenda packet.

1546
02:40:33,792 --> 02:40:39,214
And one of the things that we're really hoping to see and get is certainty moving forward.

1547
02:40:40,394 --> 02:40:42,055
So for example, to see that

1548
02:40:43,155 --> 02:40:44,796
there's a requirement for a shadow study.

1549
02:40:44,956 --> 02:40:46,977
And as a developer, that's one of the things we always get concerned about.

1550
02:40:47,377 --> 02:40:53,500
Not because we're opposed to doing them, but because there's never any sort of metric defined as to what is actually a good and bad shadow study.

1551
02:40:53,520 --> 02:41:03,065
And to see that there's the two-hour daylight requirement, just reading that as an example, tells me that you guys have thought this through when you're trying to be helpful to giving everyone certainty so we can move forward together.

1552
02:41:03,445 --> 02:41:05,306
So it's just very encouraging to me.

1553
02:41:06,487 --> 02:41:12,470
The issue that I wanted to speak on tonight, and again, you don't need to hear much about me.

1554
02:41:13,432 --> 02:41:18,136
Worked in development, worked as an engineer, and I've had a lot of experience with this.

1555
02:41:21,923 --> 02:41:24,805
We wanted to suggest an additional defined use.

1556
02:41:26,267 --> 02:41:30,270
It's known in the business as purpose-built student housing.

1557
02:41:30,470 --> 02:41:35,914
We can call it private student housing, you can call it what you want, but it's a use that doesn't really fit into the categories as defined.

1558
02:41:36,635 --> 02:41:42,319
It is what Director Hunt said is done elsewhere.

1559
02:41:42,379 --> 02:41:45,422
I'd say it's actually done quite frequently around this country, in fact,

1560
02:41:45,962 --> 02:42:00,198
even in this area, often it ends up becoming a public-private partnership, but in this case, you know, we're suggesting that it just be allowed as a private use, which is student housing, but not necessarily owned or affiliated with the university.

1561
02:42:02,707 --> 02:42:03,607
This is of scale.

1562
02:42:04,047 --> 02:42:10,629
We're not thinking about this of small developments, but a larger scale development that would be managed.

1563
02:42:10,910 --> 02:42:13,890
So it would feel a lot like the dorm definition, right?

1564
02:42:15,251 --> 02:42:18,372
It would feel like a dorm, but it's not owned by the university.

1565
02:42:18,932 --> 02:42:24,394
It's private, it's taxable, and there's ways to enforce that it's actually used only by students.

1566
02:42:24,894 --> 02:42:30,535
It's not like an apartment building because it wouldn't be set up to be open to just the general public.

1567
02:42:30,575 --> 02:42:32,116
It would be specific for students.

1568
02:42:32,156 --> 02:42:35,016
These developers like to do this because for two reasons.

1569
02:42:35,937 --> 02:42:38,857
When folks send their kids away to school, they want to know that they're living in student housing.

1570
02:42:39,498 --> 02:42:46,119
And the universities are more likely to funnel students to these developments if it's truly student housing versus something that is taken on the general public.

1571
02:42:46,139 --> 02:42:47,800
So we'd like to see this as a defined use.

1572
02:42:48,720 --> 02:42:49,661
What does this solve?

1573
02:42:50,982 --> 02:43:05,992
I think it's pretty clear that they, you know, with not all the university students being housed on campus, and we're going to, you know, Tufts is the most proximate university obviously, this has an impact on the affordability and the availability of housing to the general public.

1574
02:43:07,112 --> 02:43:17,054
We can keep the students in the family size units, but if you create another opportunity, either a dorm through the university or something like this, you can really alleviate the pressure that that creates in the local housing market.

1575
02:43:17,494 --> 02:43:35,417
So a 600-bed building, which would be a larger building, could reduce the displacement of 150 to 200 apartments that could be opened up to families or other young professionals or otherwise, because this would create an opportunity to get them out of that housing stock.

1576
02:43:36,245 --> 02:43:45,327
Currently, there are 2,000 plus students living off campus in Medford, both undergrad and graduate, 3,600 between the two communities of Somerville and Medford.

1577
02:43:46,587 --> 02:43:51,708
I went on CoStar, which is a private, you know, is an aggregator of rental information.

1578
02:43:52,188 --> 02:44:02,410
The average monthly rent on CoStar in Medford, which is, this is going to be the larger development, so this doesn't poll every single unit in Medford, was just over $3,000 a unit.

1579
02:44:04,713 --> 02:44:07,514
If you do a half mile radius around the center of Tufts, it's 4,300.

1580
02:44:07,854 --> 02:44:15,596
The impact that Tufts has, you know, the students themselves have on the housing cost is significant.

1581
02:44:15,616 --> 02:44:20,798
I can't necessarily attribute all of that difference to the students, but there's certainly some portion of it.

1582
02:44:22,439 --> 02:44:32,342
So you can establish a use and require that it, you know, either they have an MOU with the university, that they accept the students, they're going to enforce the code of conduct,

1583
02:44:33,552 --> 02:44:37,215
You know, these buildings would be staffed to professionally manage their scale.

1584
02:44:38,336 --> 02:44:45,581
And you can have an enforcement mechanism that, you know, that would run with the building's certificate of occupancy.

1585
02:44:45,641 --> 02:44:47,342
So the building department has the ability to enforce that.

1586
02:44:47,362 --> 02:44:51,605
It is truly occupied by students and that's what developers of this kind of thing want.

1587
02:44:53,167 --> 02:44:53,627
Parking.

1588
02:44:54,372 --> 02:44:56,475
is another thing that is different with students.

1589
02:44:56,495 --> 02:44:57,877
Students tend to have fewer cars.

1590
02:44:58,037 --> 02:44:59,319
They're there for a short period of time.

1591
02:44:59,359 --> 02:44:59,920
They're there to learn.

1592
02:44:59,940 --> 02:45:01,222
They're not there to go drive around.

1593
02:45:01,242 --> 02:45:03,605
I know that that was the case when I was in college locally here.

1594
02:45:05,517 --> 02:45:14,942
Tufts reports that 16 percent of students occupied by single occupancy vehicle but the majority of that number is probably off campus, you know, commuters and not necessarily residents of the area.

1595
02:45:15,462 --> 02:45:18,744
So there is evidence that there's not a lot of demand for cars for students.

1596
02:45:19,765 --> 02:45:29,230
We'd suggest something in the order of 0.15 to 0.25 parking spaces per bed be something that we'd include in a use like this which is consistent with

1597
02:45:30,178 --> 02:45:34,847
the dormitory definition of one space per four beds, just because there just isn't that demand.

1598
02:45:34,867 --> 02:45:37,171
And I think this would operate very similarly to that.

1599
02:45:37,191 --> 02:45:38,774
Sorry, David.

1600
02:45:39,736 --> 02:45:41,797
That's quite all right, as long as that wasn't me.

1601
02:45:42,817 --> 02:45:44,858
Well, no, that was the timer.

1602
02:45:44,918 --> 02:45:46,418
Oh, fantastic.

1603
02:45:46,438 --> 02:45:47,538
So that was the end of it.

1604
02:45:47,578 --> 02:45:49,979
So we're suggesting that this be considered as a use.

1605
02:45:50,219 --> 02:45:53,620
You know, there's other things that we have opinions on of what came out tonight.

1606
02:45:53,640 --> 02:45:56,181
But this use, it doesn't fit into the bucket of dormitory.

1607
02:45:56,201 --> 02:45:58,422
It doesn't fit in the bucket of multifamily.

1608
02:45:58,542 --> 02:46:00,323
It's a specific thing that's in between.

1609
02:46:03,043 --> 02:46:03,323
Thank you.

1610
02:46:03,423 --> 02:46:03,764
Thank you.

1611
02:46:03,884 --> 02:46:08,065
And I think if you could share some of that with the planning

1612
02:46:09,435 --> 02:46:12,536
We have a copy and we can share that with the members of the council.

1613
02:46:12,556 --> 02:46:20,000
Yeah, so we'll share that with all of the Community Development Board and the Planning Development Sustainability and appreciate the comment.

1614
02:46:21,520 --> 02:46:23,321
Alright, anyone else in the chamber?

1615
02:46:23,341 --> 02:46:28,503
I'm not seeing anyone right now, so I'll go in order of the folks I saw on Zoom.

1616
02:46:29,364 --> 02:46:36,887
I'm gonna allow you guys to turn on your video and we'll go to Judy Weinstock.

1617
02:46:38,005 --> 02:46:39,698
Name and address for the record, please.

1618
02:46:41,863 --> 02:46:44,826
Hi, everybody, Judy Weinstock at 144 Burgett.

1619
02:46:45,226 --> 02:46:54,194
I wanted to make a suggestion, perhaps Paola and Alicia and Danielle can decide if this is a good idea or not.

1620
02:46:54,775 --> 02:47:07,566
I actually think that this definitions issue that we're having between co-housing, dormitory, fraternity, sorority, apartment building, and thus and on and on and on, not to mention this brand new

1621
02:47:08,387 --> 02:47:18,591
category that was just presented, I actually think we need a table of requirements because trying to define these things in prose just actually hasn't worked.

1622
02:47:18,651 --> 02:47:20,351
I think it's very confusing.

1623
02:47:20,911 --> 02:47:31,555
I think that if there are characteristics that are associated with each of these different forms of housing or living situation, that they ought to be enunciated in a table.

1624
02:47:32,103 --> 02:47:33,924
that would make it just so much easier.

1625
02:47:34,064 --> 02:47:38,187
It would be like the use table where the characteristics are in columns above.

1626
02:47:38,467 --> 02:47:43,850
And if the type of housing met a particular characteristic, they'd have a check mark.

1627
02:47:43,910 --> 02:47:45,612
And if they didn't, they would say no.

1628
02:47:46,072 --> 02:47:49,814
And I do think that it will help the public to really understand the differences.

1629
02:47:50,254 --> 02:47:58,860
I understand that the categories across the top could be incredibly broad and long, but they need to be specific enough that you can actually tell the difference

1630
02:47:59,677 --> 02:48:12,630
between this dormitory proposal that was just proposed and the dormitory that, by the way, will house 650 students at Tufts when it opens in two years or a year and a half.

1631
02:48:14,051 --> 02:48:21,018
What distinguishes those two proposals in a manner that not just the board can understand, but that the public can actually understand?

1632
02:48:21,959 --> 02:48:24,843
Um, you know, I think there's gonna be lots of time.

1633
02:48:24,923 --> 02:48:26,825
I hope to talk about things like parking.

1634
02:48:26,905 --> 02:48:28,647
